Journal of Visual Languages & Computing

Volume 41, August 2017, Pages 22-40

Supporting group collaboration in an annotation system

Author links open overlay panelDaniloAvolaaPaoloBottoniaAmjadHawash1b
https://doi.org/10.1016/j.jvlc.2017.04.004Get rights and content

Highlights

•

Group-based services supporting cooperation introduced to a Web annotation tool.

•

Formal model of groups, of operations on them and of security mechanisms.

•

Details on the overall architecture and core implementation mechanisms.

•

Presentation of Technology-Enhanced Learning applicative scenarios and experimental tests.

Abstract

a common practice when interacting with digital documents, allowing the addition of information to existing data without corrupting them. Restricting visibility of annotations to groups of users, as usually enforced in enterprise collaboration systems, turns annotations into a tool for focused collaboration among users with common interests. However, providing different levels of visibility in an open Web-based environment is challenging, due to conflicting needs: to keep the annotation process simple, to ensure adequate levels of privacy and confidence to users, and to allow users to filter out irrelevant information. We describe a suite of services for group formation and management, integrated into the existing MADCOW annotation system. We also propose a formal characterisation of groups, introducing atomic operations on which complex functionalities are based. The paper discusses different scenarios and applications and argues for the usability of the proposed integration by presenting the results of experimental tests.

1. Introduction

Web pages, without altering the page content, thus transforming extemporary observations occurring during normal browsing into persistent, additional and shareable information. This may enhance (asynchronous) cooperation among visitors with common interests who can annotate different resources with respect to relevant topics [23]. Reasons for annotating can vary: to create mementos or clarifications of interesting content; to entertain discussions with other users; to construct or integrate documents [1], [4], [18], or in the context of training and educational processes [9], [22], [26]. Annotations have also been used to foster collaboration between users and developers in a mashup platform [2], [3].

In the MADCOW annotation system2, users create annotations of multimedia content, such as text, images, or video clips, embedded in a Web page [8]. The original MADCOW setting offered just two types of annotation: private, viewable only by their authors, and public, viewed by any MADCOW user visiting an annotated page. Public annotations enhance collaboration by supporting online discussions, but they reduce privacy and security for users [20], [27]. Conversely, private annotations guarantee privacy and security, at the expense of collaboration. Even with these restrictions, MADCOW already supported forms of collaborative interaction on annotations such as: production of same content, creation of annotation threads, or annotation of pages generated from already existing annotations, as reported in [8]. In that paper we also showed how to circumvent the collaboration vs. privacy and security conflict inherent to the limitations of the private/public alternative by setting up private accounts for specific tasks, with credentials shared among trusted partners. Obviously, collaboration at community or enterprise level.

Hence, the main motivation for developing the group facilities described in this paper was the need for first-class mechanisms for sharing annotations among MADCOW users with common interests, allowing them to collaborate while maintaining focus on specific, annotated material. At the same time, group-level access allows the hiding of information from external users. By joining groups, MADCOW users can collaborate with members of choice and enjoy a finer form of access control: an annotation published to a group is viewable by any group member, while public annotations remain visible to any MADCOW user and private ones are viewed by their submitters only.

In order to cater for full management of groups, we also provide a collection of operations, based on two main concepts: merging and separation of groups, to adapt group composition to the evolution of members’ interests. Merging operations produce one new group from existing ones, while separation produces two groups out of a single one. A set of atomic operations allows the modular construction and straightforward implementation of more complex ones.

In addition to the impact on access policies and the possibility of generating discussion threads focused on both annotated content and specific topics, introducing groups to the MADCOW system also reduces bandwidth occupation, as only annotations of concern to the group are retrieved from the server. While a proof of concept was given in [7], this paper describes a complete realisation of the notion of group and of the related services within MADCOW.

Integrating these services within the MADCOW framework provides a rich offering of facilities to users, combining different methods for annotating several types of content with different policies for publishing the produced annotations. Based on an analysis of existing tools (see Section 2), such a combination appears to be unique. Experimental tests and pilot studies, reported on in Section 6, seem to confirm the appropriateness of the proposed tools to promote collaboration through annotations.

Paper organisation. Section 2 surveys related work on Web annotation and group support and Section 3, after briefly describing the MADCOW system’s basic features, presents three motivating scenarios and derives requirements for groups. Section 4 provides a formal description of the notions introduced to meet the requirements and Section 5 contains a technical description of the realisation of group services in MADCOW toghether with concrete examples of the realised interfaces. After reporting on user tests in 6 User tests, 7 Conclusions and future work discusses conclusions and future work.

2. Related work

Several annotation tools in various domains, e.g. social networks, medical discussions, Technology-Enhanced Learning, support forms of collaboration among annotators. Of these, while most just supply public annotations, see e.g. Draw Here [35], FloatNotes [37] and InterNote [39]. Even within tools allowing formation of groups, little support is given to group management, making the transfer of annotations across groups difficult.

Annotation tools. For the “kind of application” dimension, we have independent desktop applications, such as EverNote [36], or special browsers integrating annotation features, e.g. A.nnotate [29] or Webmarcation Annotator [38]. The MADCOW client was integrated in standard browsers as a bookmarklet [8], while the version discussed in this paper is installed on the Firefox browser as a toolbar and a drop-down menu providing access to various services.

submitting and displaying annotations, in several domains, such as telemedicine, peer reviews and e-Research. By providing clinicians and researchers with the necessary support for maintaining confidentiality and protecting both intellectual property and personal privacy associated with their annotations, they will be more willing to share their views and engage in inter-organizational and inter-disciplinary collaborations. Khan et al. [19] addressed these issues by implementing a security layer for the Annotea server, based on a combination of open source technologies. The modular design and use of interoperable technologies makes it possible to easily extend the server to support annotation of additional resource types or to use it as a standard public annotation server. Notes and annotations could be encrypted before being shared among different users. ARALOC [30] is an annotation tool designed for tablets which encrypts all annotations submitted by users as an attempt to create a secured environment to enable annotation sharing.

With respect to privacy, few tools support the distinction between private and public annotations. The Diigo Toolbar [33] enables users to comment on others’ notes. DocumentCloud [34] is a Web-based platform to support journalists in the search, analysis, annotation and publication of documents used in reporting. Public notes are visible to anyone with access to the document, a private one only to its author.

Annotation sharing is supported by ShiftSpace [42] and Stikis [45]. In offline annotation systems, e.g. JumpKnowledge [40], content is annotated. The CDAC Annotation System 1 (no longer supported) saved annotations on the user’s PC instead of a server.

Group support mechanisms are being introduced: the Diigo Toolbar [33] lets users create their own groups and invite other members, and provides some services for group archiving and groups dissemination, such as adding group links to users’ websites and publishing group contents in blogs. A.nnotate [29] takes a snapshot of a document, Web page or image, to produce a read-only copy, which can be annotated and shared with other users. This does not amount exactly to group annotation, but the tool implements it in a group-like fashion. In Bounce [31], users produce notes for snapshots of Web pages and collaborate on them with other users. In Stickis [44], user groups implement the idea of private annotation submission. In Reframe It [43], users can comment on a Web page via a sidebar and reply to others. Crocodoc [32] does not implement groups, but users can invite others to collaborate in real-time by sharing folders. All of these systems simulate the grouping of users by having users collaborate through annotations. Except for Diigo, there are no actual groups, i.e. no identified entities that contain sets of members with their annotations. Although Diigo has the facility of creating and managing groups, it lacks the merging and splitting features to create new groups from existing ones.

In [14], users classify and organise documents based on annotations performed via the Yawas [47] highlighting system. Classification of documents occurs by first grouping related annotations and then grouping the associated documents in one cluster. Another similar approach is followed in [24]. They condensate Web documents into simpler contents, called statements, and apply annotations on them to indicate agreement or disagreement. Grouping of documents depends on the annotation results.

The work in [21] considers the annotation of data inside databases and their propagation and merging through queries. This requires the definition of an appropriate algebraic structure to deal with dependencies between merged annotations.

The introduction of groups to MADCOW makes it different from systems supporting groups or group-like operations in that it provides: (a) role-based access control, based on the distinction between status and privilege, together with the definition of a specific isolation policy within a group; (b) group manipulation through merge and separation operations; (c) deletion policies for defining what happens to members and annotations when a group is deleted.

3. Working scenarios

Depending on the type of medium at hand, the creation of annotations with the MADCOW system entails the selection of text, the drawing of a rectangle over an image, or the selection of sequences of frames from a video clip in the page. Any of these actions activates a pop-up window in which users can write their own notes and input some annotation-related data, such as tags or the groups to which the note must be posted, as shown in Fig. 1, while other metadata, such as author and date, are automatically captured. Production and retrieval of annotations are enabled/disabled via the MADCOW toolbar (Fig. 2), which is composed of three buttons associated with JavaScript code to communicate with the DOM (Document Object Model) trees of the visited pages: the Home button brings users to the MADCOW portal where they can use commands accessible through the menus for creating, managing, and joining groups (Fig. 3); the Enable Notes button enables/disables the annotation process; the Display Notes button activates the display of annotations for the current Web page.

We present three scenarios illustrating some of the possibilities offered by group-related annotations in the MADCOW system and describing its usage in both public and restricted settings.

3.1. Technology-Enhanced Learning: Scenario 1

In the first scenario, relative to Technology-Enhanced Learning, Taya is a university lecturer who wants to promote discussion and increase collaboration among students by having them annotate course-related online resources. However, she wants discussions to be restricted within students, who would feel otherwise exposed to external criticism. She creates three groups related to her “Database” course, where her students can conduct online discussions on materials and homeworks. She also publishes online quizzes, where students can use annotations to answer questions. The three groups are:

1.

“Database Material”, to discuss Web pages related to the course subjects.

2.

“Database Homeworks”, to discuss homeworks published online. Participation in this group is not mandatory since a student has a choice to either participate in homeworks or prepare a report related to the material.

3.

“Database Quizzes”, to answer prepared quizzes by annotating the questions with the proper answers.

Through her MADCOW account Taya creates the first group and sets its properties so that: (a) each member can see all annotations posted to the group; (b) only invited students can join the group; (c) no other user can find out about it; (d) when the group is closed, students are not redirected to other groups.

For the second group, she establishes that students can see annotations by their colleagues, while any MADCOW user can see the group name and apply to join. Again, when the group is closed, students will not be redirected to other groups.

Finally, she creates the third group with properties preventing students to see other members’ answers at the time of the quiz. The group is hidden from other users and only invited students can join it. As she needs some teaching assistant to help her with quizzes, she selects Daniello to be a moderator. Finally when the group is deleted, its members will be transferred to the existing “All Quizzes” group, gathering all the students who participated in some quiz during the course.

Taya starts inviting students to the “Database Material” group by selecting those registered to the course from the list of available users, using a system-generated, editable invitation message.

Daniel (a student in the Database course) is notified of invitations from Taya as well as from others (as a writer for the “C++ Programming” and “Database Material” groups and as a reader for the “Operating Systems” group) for each of which he has the option of accepting or refusing. He accepts the one from Taya and postpones the decision about the invitation as reader.

Cristina, a student who needs to work on the homeworks track, searches for the proper group. Checking the information on it, she is reassured it is the correct group, so she completes and sends her application.

On her next access to the MADCOW portal, Taya accepts all the new requests for her groups, including the one from Cristina. She also checks that the list of writers for “Database Material” includes all invitees. Similarly, Daniello is now able to invite users to “Database Quizzes”.

When Calvitto browses the online material for Taya’s course, he produces some annotation and posts it on the “Database Material” group, making it the starting point for some online discussion.

Students can view annotations posted to the course groups. For the “Database Material” group, which is not isolated, they can also view annotations by their colleagues.

As a group owner, Taya has the privilege to delete annotations or change their expiry dates (other members can only perform these actions on annotations they posted). She notices that two members of the “Database Material” group are misusing the annotation process, so she adds both of them to the group’s blacklist. As a result, their status is changed to prevent them from submitting annotations to the group.

3.2. Collaboration in a grassroot committee

Marco, a MADCOW user, is a member of a local grassroot committee of the Prenestino neighbourhood in Rome, and frequently looks for news and comments concerning Prenestino, annotating them with tags which identify the arguments touched upon in the material, and sometimes adding extended comments on them. He has promoted this style of collecting information and putting it in context through annotations, and now there are several MADCOW users in his committee. In order to support collaboration on the annotated content, he creates a MADCOW group “Prenestino” dedicated to the neighbourhood, inviting the other committee members to it.

As the number of annotations in the group begins to grow, Marco decides to create several groups on specific issues of interest, such as “Environment”, “Transportation”, “Schools”, while leaving the “Prenestino” group for more general annotations.

The “Environment” group is one of the most active, with annotations focusing on two topics: “Pollution”, as the area suffers heavy traffic, and “Parks”, as there are a few parks, but not well cared for. Therefore Marco extracts two groups, dedicated to these two topics, from the “Environment” group and appoints Arianna and Enzo as their respective owners.

Marco has initially set the group as open, i.e. anyone can join it directly. When somebody starts writing libelous comments, he blacklist their authors and decides to change policy, so that an application is requested.

However, the committee does not want to renounce some level of publicity, so they keep posting some public annotations and leave the visibility of the “Prenestino” group public. As a result, Rosa, a resident of the area, gets to know the group and applies for participation in it.

Other MADCOW users are also interested in analogous topics and have posted public annotations. Arianna, the responsible for the “Transportation” group, while querying the MADCOW portal for notes about this general topic, notices some interesting comments by Dando, and decides to invite him to join the group.

3.3. Technology-Enhanced Learning: Scenario 2

For his course “Programming with Java”, Aldo wants to experiment the use of MADCOW as a support for the correction of students’ mini-projects, consisting in commented Java programs. Hence, he requires students to post their answers as HTML pages to a specific repository, reachable only by tutors and teaching assistants within the University intranet, who can then use MADCOW to annotate portions of the answers that they deem incorrect. Aldo needs to test various features of the programs, e.g. errors and program readability, and creates a group for each feature, to which he invites teaching assistants as writers or readers. By being simple annotation readers, members can gain some insight in the error correction process and improve their performance in the groups in which they are appointed as writers. Aldo creates the following groups:

1.

“General Errors” (writers: Alessio, Tazia, Tea and Angelina; readers: Aberto).

2.

“Smaller Line Count” (writers: Alessio, Edwardo and Dando; readers: Tea and Aberto).

3.

“Code Regions” (writers: Tazia, Tea, Dando and Angelina).

4.

“Runtime Errors” (writers: Alessio, Tazia and Aberto).

5.

“Naming Conventions” (writers: Alessio and Angelina; readers: Aberto).

After the correction process is started, Aldo notices that Alessio and Tazia are concentrating on logical errors, so he decides to extract a “Logical Errors” subgroup from “General Errors”, composed by the two of them and by Aberto as reader.

As annotations to both groups “Smaller Line Count” and “Code Regions” are concerned with code readability, Aldo merges them to form a “Readability Check” group. The original groups are deleted and anybody who was a writer in one of the original groups will be a writer in the new one.

Aldo notices that members who are writers in both the “Runtime Errors” and “Logical Errors” groups submit the same annotations to both groups. Hence, he creates a more specific group from the intersection of members. Only members who are writers in both groups will be writers in the new one.

Later on, he realises that writers of “Naming Conventions” are submitting most of their annotations both to this group and to “Readability Check” and subsumes the first group into the second one.

3.4. Requirements from scenarios

The previous scenarios indicate which services are required to be provided by MADCOW for group management.

REQ1

Users should be able to create groups, invite members to their groups, apply for joining existing groups, accept or refuse invitations.

REQ2

Group owners should be able to manage the status of members, by promoting some to the role of moderator, as well as blacklisting members for inappropriate behaviour.

REQ3

All annotations in a group must be visible to the owner, but common members could be restricted to see annotations from others.

REQ4

The system should support search for groups. An owner can decide to restrict the visibility of a group.

REQ5

A group owner should be able to configure all the group properties, including the modality of joining and the destination of members and their annotations when a group is deleted.

REQ6

Owners should be able to manage creation, deletion, and composition of groups by merging, extracting, intersecting or subsuming them, or removing individual members.

MADCOW users can play two roles with respect to groups, user and group member, with associated status and privileges.

1.

User: any MADCOW user is granted basic privileges to:

(a)

Create a group, thereby becoming its owner (REQ1).

(b)

Submit/delete annotations to the MADCOW system, not restricted to groups.

(c)

Accept or refuse invitations to be a reader or writer in other groups (REQ1).

(d)

Search for groups (REQ4).

(e)

Directly join public groups or apply for joining non-public ones (REQ1, REQ5).

2.

Group Member: a user belonging to a group receives privilege and status from the group owner or moderators. For member privileges we have:

(a)

reader, able to view all the annotations in the group, if the latter is not isolated (REQ3).

(b)

writer, with the additional capability of submitting annotations and possibly deleting those published by him/herself.

(c)

group owner: the user who created the group has writer capabilities and can:

i

Perform operations on owned groups (REQ6).

ii

Change the group properties (REQ5).

iii

Invite other users to join the group (as readers or writers) (REQ1).

iv

Remove members (REQ6).

v

Manage the status and privileges of members of owned groups (REQ2).

The owner of a group is always unique. Ownership cannot be revoked, other than by deleting the group, and the owner cannot be expelled from a group.

As for status, a member can be:
(a)

A moderator, who acts on behalf of the owner to manage:

i

invitations, applications and expulsions;

ii

the group blacklist.

(b)

A blacklisted member, who is not authorised to submit annotations to the group.

(c)

A normal member, with standard writer or reader privileges.

4. Formal characterization of groups

In order to meet the requirements in Section 3.4, we have extended the formal model of annotations in [12], in line with the one presented in [1], with an abstract specification of the properties of groups and of the operations for their management.

The model relies on the presence in the overall MADCOW specification of the two domains U, the set of all MADCOW users, and A, the set of all MADCOW annotations, and of a function α: A → U mapping each annotation to its author. In order to define groups, we increment the MADCOW specification with the sets of: identifiers, I; groups, G; and group names, N.

We introduce a number of domains, which formalize various group and member properties, such as privileges (Pri) and status (Sts) described in Section 3.4. We also introduce the collection of properties {JM, SG, IG, AD} for defining the join method, whether a group is searchable or isolated and what policy to follow after a group is deleted, respectively, together with a set of operations needed in merging processes to combine different values for the same property, as specified in Table 1, Table 2, Table 3, Table 4.

Table 1. JM composition.

jm1jm2⊖
PPP
PAA
PII
APA
AAA
AII
IPI
IAI
III

Table 2. SG composition.

Table 3. IG composition.

LLL

CCC

Table 4. AD composition.

More specifically, we define:

•

Pri={WRI,REA,OWN}.

•

Sts={NORM,MOD,BLK}.

•

JM={PUBLIC,INVITE,APPLY}, together with an operation ⊖.

•

SG={SEARCHABLE,NON_SEARCHABLE}, with operation ⊗.

•

IG={ISOLATED,NON_ISOLATED}, with operation ⊘.

•

AD={REGULAR,TRANSFERRED}, with operation ⊙.

The Joining_Method property defines how users can become members of a group. It can assume one of the values in JM: If its value is PUBLIC (P in Table 1), users can freely become members of a group, without the need for authorisation from the owner or the moderators (collectively auths). With INVITE (I), participation in a group can only occur following an invitation from auths, while with APPLY (A) users have to issue a request to be granted by auths.

The Searchable_Group property, with values in SG, states that non-member users may search for a SEARCHABLE (S in Table 2) group, or they may not, if the value is NON_SEARCHABLE (N).

The Isolated_Group property, with values in IG, indicates whether group members may view annotations by others (value ISOLATED, L in Table 3) or not (value NON_ISOLATED, C).

After_Delete takes values in AD. If its value is REGULAR (R in Table 4), members are simply removed from a deleted group, while a value of TRANSFERRED (T) indicates that they are added as members to other groups (specified in a separate property).

We first present an informal description of group-related operations and then provide a formal treatment in terms of abstract data types in Specification 1 (see Fig. 4).

The first two operations, namely create and delete, are the group constructor and destructor, while all the others are assumed to operate on the group resulting from some initial application of create.

Operation create creates a new group and assigns the set of its properties. The group name must be unique, i.e. the identifier for the new group must not appear already in N. The same condition applies to the execution of the rename operation.

Operation delete deletes the group. According to the property AD, its members are either transferred to other groups owned by the same owner or just removed from the deleted group and their grouped annotations are converted to private ones.

Operation addMbr realises the addition of members to a group, according to the JM joining method property.

Operation rmvMbr removes members from a group and cannot be applied to the group owner.

Operation chgPriv modifies the privileges of a single user, while the chgStatus operation changes his or her status. Neither of these operations can be applied to the group owner.

The addition of an annotation to a group, addAnn, like its inverse removal rmvAnn, requires that the annotation be produced by a member of the group with writer privileges. Addition and deletion must also update the mapping α.

All other operations retrieve the corresponding properties, without particular conditions. Notice that there is no operation to change the group owner.

With Specification 1, in Fig. 4, we present groups as abstract data types constructed on the above domains, using the classical notation of [15]. Here, the sorts section lists the data types on which the new type, in bold, is defined, the opns section presents the signatures of the operations defined on the data types, as maps between sets of sorts, and the eqns sections defines the overall semantics for the operations in an abstract, mutually recursive, way, independent of any implementation, providing the essential properties required to implementations in terms of equalities between sequences of applications of these operations. Each sort is valued on the domain with the same name. By SEQ=SEQ′(create(n,o,j,r,i,a)) we denote any sequence of operations starting with group creation and continuing with a subsequence SEQ′ in which the group is not deleted, nor is the property queried in the equation altered. Also, for simplicity we do not mention that all queries actually preserve the group. ℘ (X) denotes the powerset of the set X, i.e. the set of all its subsets. The operations create and delete operate also on G and N (adding and removing groups and names). For simplicity, in the equations we leave implicit in the arguments of the operations these sets and only consider the effect of operations on a group. When the execution of an operation is guarded by some predicate, we present it within brackets. Each predicate must hold before the operation is applied.

The abstract data types formalisation provides a precise specification of services and facilitates the design of new services as iterative composition of operations.

We also define four operations on G, resulting in the creation (and possible deletion) of groups: Extraction, deriving two groups from an existing one, and Subsumption, GroupUnion, and GroupIntersection, which take as arguments two groups and generate a new one. The properties of the new groups are derived from those for the original groups using Table 1, Table 2, Table 3, Table 4. We extend the group data type by the corresponding operations and equations. For each complex operation, its realisation in terms of atomic operations is also presented in Appendix A, where for simplicity, we use explicit assignments and continuations. In the MADCOW implementation all operations can be directly activated by the group owner or result as side effect of complex operations merging or separating existing groups.

Group extraction

The extraction operation creates a new group, G2 of name n2, with selected members (and their annotations) out of an existing one, G1. One of the selected members becomes the owner, while G1 is left unaltered. Therefore, we add to group the operation and equations described in Specification A.1 in Appendix A, where we show the effect of the operations on the created group. The effect of extraction on G and N can be represented as:

•

N@post=N@pre∪{n2}

•

G@post=G@pre∪{G2}.

Here and in the following the suffix @pre indicates the set content before applying the operation and the suffix @post the content after application.

Group union

The union operation creates a new group, G3 of name n3, by combining members and the associated annotations from two existing groups, G1 and G2, of name n1 and n2. One of the shared members is selected as the owner of the new group. We add to group the operation and equations described in Specification A.2 in Appendix A. Two boolean parameters indicate whether the two united groups are to be kept or deleted (with the consequent effect on G and N), and which level of privilege must be retained for members in both groups, respectively. Independently of the values of these parameters, the following hold:

•

N@post∖{n1,n2}=(N@pre∖{n1,n2})∪{n3}

•

G@post∖{G1,G2}=(G@pre∖{G1,G2})∪{G3}.

Group intersection

The intersection operation creates a new group, G3 of name n3, with members taken from the shared members of two existing groups, {G1, G2}, of name {n1, n2}, respectively. One of the common members is selected as owner. The original groups remain unaltered. The following hold:

•

N@post=N@pre∪{n3}

•

G@post=G@pre∪{G3}.

We add to group the operation and equations in Specification A.3 in Appendix A.

Group subsumption

The subsumption operation modifies the composition of a group G2 by adding to it the members and annotations of another group G1, of name n1 if the set of members of G1 is a subset of the set of members of G2. G1 is then deleted. Therefore we add to group the operation and equations described in Specification A.4 in Appendix A, while the effect on G and N of the subsumption operation is described by:

•

G@post=G@pre∖{G1}

•

N@post=N@pre∖{n1}.

Fig. 5 illustrates graphically the four operations, where

represents a group, a group owner, a writer, a reader, and an annotation linked to a writer. In Fig. 5(b), for union, “U1” is a reader in G′ and a writer in G′′, hence a writer in G as merOpt is true. For “U2”, the case of merOpt= false is illustrated. Similar for intersection (Fig. 5(c)). With subsumption no option is given, but differences in privilege are reconciled by giving subsumed members the privilege they enjoy in the subsuming group. In Fig. 5(d), “U1”, a reader in G′′ and a writer in G′, becomes a writer in G, while “U2”, a writer in G′′ and a reader in G′, becomes a reader.

5. Implementing groups

In order to implement the formal specification of groups discussed in Section 4, we extended the MADCOW database so as to accommodate group properties and defined mechanisms for group-related annotations, while preserving the original MADCOW interaction for posting and retrieving annotations. In this section we describe the technical aspects of this realisation, in particular those concerning the database and the communication among components.

5.1. System architecture

MADCOW relies on a 3-tiered architecture (see Fig. 6), described in detail in [11], in which the client side is represented by the MADCOW toolbar, installed in the Firefox browser, that interacts with the DOM of the loaded Web page to create or display related annotations. In particular:

•

Presentation deals with management of user interaction activities.

•

Processing controls service execution for requests from Presentation.

•

Database deals with management of data traffic with Processing and of database transactions.

The layered organisation already provides a first level of security [10], as users cannot access the system database other than by interacting with the presentation layer [25]; introducing groups allows a fine-tuned management of data security: users cannot submit or read annotations in groups they do not belong to and PHP sessions control the delivery of subsequent pages handling users’ requests and system replies.

MADCOW harnesses Web and database servers to maintain and handle users’ annotations and accounts. On the (fat) client side, pages are presented based on their HTML and CSS specifications, with the support of JavaScript functions for data validation, thus minimising data traffic between the clients and the MADCOW server, saving both bandwidth and server load [16]. Users can post and retrieve annotations, on which additional services can be built, e.g. statistics or information extraction. Exploiting AJAX techniques, JavaScript code is maintained on the client side (by loading it to the instance of the Firefox browser from which the user is interacting), either in the MADCOW toolbar, for management of annotations, or in the MADCOW portal, for management of groups. In either case, XMLHttpRequest objects are generated to manage data traffic between the client and the server. On the server side, invoking any PHP function activates MySQL queries for database access and updates. As a general mechanism, when the user asks to retrieve data relative to annotated portions of the current Web page, the generated instance of XMLHttpRequest opens a logical connection with the server and sends the data needed to identify the annotated portion and retrieve its related annotations, while the user ID is taken from the current PHP session.

Data returned by the server is processed by other JavaScript code in the MADCOW toolbar to instrument the DOM of the current page with new nodes, allowing the highlight of the annotated portions, and with code to activate a pop-up window. This window interacts with PHP code on the server side to retrieve the actual content of the annotations which can be served to the current user and to allow interaction with them.

5.2. Extensions to the MADCOW database

The Entity-Relationship diagrams in Figs. 7 and 8 show the overall schema resulting from the addition of groups to the MADCOW annotation database, refining the scheme in [11]. Annotations are associated with: the group(s) the annotation is posted to; the annotation actual content and its attachments; the annotation author; information defining the selected part of the page (for example start and end for text or video); the URL of the annotated resource, together with specific properties.

All the properties discussed in Section 4 are persisted in the database, and information on each group is related to its owner, together with the information on the creation date. The relation afterDeleteGroups is represented by storing the identifiers of the groups to which members are migrated upon deletion of the original group.

5.3. System behaviour

We discuss messages and data movements in the MADCOW group management system with reference to the component and deployment diagrams of Figs. 9 and 10.

The realisation of the system User Interface, using HTML and CSS code, relies on XUL for the definition of the MADCOW toolbar (see Fig. 2 in Section 3). We give an overview of the relevant behaviours for the processes of posting and retrieving textual annotations in the context of groups. The same mechanisms apply to the annotation of images or video clips.

Installing the MADCOW toolbar on the user version of Firefox causes the creation of a JavaScript object (called the MADCOWToolBar) for each launch of the browser. The MADCOWToolBar maintains a set of properties and is endowed with a set of functions, used to control data movement between the browser and the Web server, or to be executed on the DOM tree of each page visited by the user, in order to control the local processes related to submission and display of annotations.

Instrumenting the toolbar with code avoids the need for JavaScript injection to control the elements of the DOM tree for each visited page. The toolbar itself is specified in the XUL scripting language, and its components (buttons and drop-down menus) are linked with functions identified in the MADCOWToolBar object.

5.3.1. Using XMLHttpRequest objects

Data traffic between client and server is managed via a JavaScript XMLHttpRequest object (named sendRecObj) which acts as an intermediary between client and server. In particular, sendRecObj is used in the following processes: (1) highlighting annotated resources; (2) managing the display of possible group targets in the annotation pop-up window; (3) displaying annotations when hovering on an annotated resource; and (4) sending invitations to join a group.

Once a logical channel between client and server is open, sendRecObj sends data as pairs (item,value) populating the associative array $_POST[]. A connection with the MySQL server is then established to save data in the proper tables. Changes in the variable readyState govern the movement of data extracted from the server, stored in responseText and tokenised for transmission back to the browser.

5.3.2. Submitting annotations

After logging in a MADCOW account, a click on the “Enable Notes” toolbar button launches the function checkURL(), responsible for detecting page change events in the browser. For each page loaded on the browser, checkURL() will activate the Event.MOUSEUP event handler. After this, the system is ready for annotation processes.

Users can post annotations to any group in which they have writer capabilities, or they can just post them as public or private, without reference to groups. A pop-up window appears after the user has selected the fragment of resource to be annotated (see Fig. 1 in Section 3), offering interaction widgets by which users can: (1) write the annotation in a text area, (2) choose between private or public for visibility of a non-grouped annotation, (3) add user-defined tags, (4) choose the annotation type from a set of predefined types, (5) indicate the annotation expiry date through a calendar, and (6) choose the target group(s) for posting the annotation from the list of the groups on which the user can write. Moreover, depending on the type of the annotated resource, the following data is automatically captured and sent:

•

Text: positions, in the DOM, of the first and last selected characters.

•

Image: left upper corner coordinates and size of selection rectangle.

•

Video: timestamps for the first and last frame in a range selection.

Annotation visibility is restricted for non-grouped annotations, so posting an annotation to some group automatically sets the value of visibility to group. The titles of the groups in which the user is blacklisted appear dimmed (see Fig. 11).

The annotation date is internally saved when the user commits the choices. An annotation is automatically deleted upon expiration, or can be deleted at any moment by the group owner, or by its author, if still a writer. Readers cannot delete annotations.

5.3.3. Displaying annotations

Annotations can be viewed after logging in the MADCOW portal in a list presentation (see Fig. 12) or visiting previously annotated Web pages and activating the DisplayNotes bookmarklet, in which case they will appear in the context of the page.

In either case, sendRecObj starts an interaction with the MADCOW server to retrieve data about the annotated resources for the current Web page, filtering out those for which the user has no viewing privilege. Annotations posted to a group are always visible to the group owner and its moderators. Depending on the value of the isolated property, any member of the group can read any annotation, or only writers can view their own annotations. This can be used for example in a teaching setting, to have students perform individual exercises, while leaving full visibility on all annotations to owner and moderators.

When a user selects “My Annotations” on the MADCOW portal, the system lists all of the user’s public and private annotations. Moreover, the name of each group joined by the user is presented with an associated “Display” button to access the annotations posted to that group. For each displayed annotation, the author’s identifier is shown, together with the URL of the annotated page and its submission date (see Fig. 12). The same list appears for annotations not related to groups, where the author is understood to be the logged user. When a MADCOW user visiting a page issues a request for annotations on that page, the MADCOW server will transfer to the browser all the annotations for that page the user is entitled to view, i.e. (1) public ones; (2) all the annotations submitted by the user, be they private, or published to groups; (3) all other annotations published in non-isolated groups joined by the user.

For any retrieved annotation, the annotated fragment is highlighted on the current page in the browser and hovering on it with the mouse causes the display, in a pop-up window, of the annotations for that fragment. Hovering the mouse over a portion of an annotated resource triggers a MADCOWToolbar function that identifies the current resource and creates a pop-up window which will present the retrieved data. A sendRecObj is created to interact with the Web server to retrieve all annotations related to the hovered resource with their relative data like the annotated part, annotations and their submitters with the ability for a user to create replies, and the set of groups where each annotation is submitted.

For images and video clips, proper functions have been defined to redraw the shape enclosing the annotated portion of the image, or to put a marker icon next to the embedded video player while the annotated clip is reproduced. Also in these cases, pointing at these elements activates a pop-up window related to the annotation.

5.3.4. Managing membership

Depending on the groupJoinType and searchable properties, a MADCOW user can join a group in three ways:

1.

Public: any user can join the group as a writer.

2.

Apply: users apply to join as writers; admission is decided upon by owner/moderator.

3.

Invite: owner/moderator invites (as readers or writers) users, who can accept or refuse.

Users can join any “public” group by simply selecting those of their interest. If joining is “by application”, the process is initiated by users and is completed when the owner or a moderator accepts or refuses the application (See Figs. 13 and 14).

In processes “by invitation”, users receive invitations from auths and can accept or refuse them (see Figs. 15 and 16). Since different moderators can send invitations, the system prevents a user already invited as writer in a group from receiving an invitation as reader (writer privilege subsumes reader one), but an invitation as reader can be upgraded to one as writer.

In the latter case, if the reader invitation is accepted the writer invitation remains standing since the invited user could accept the writer invitation to upgrade his/her privilege in the group; by accepting the writer invitation, the other one, as reader, is cancelled. Owners can invite users to join through the MADCOWPortal toolbar, as described in the sequence diagram of Fig. 17. The process starts by retrieving the groups owned by the user, through a listGroups() request. For each displayed group such that groupJoinType=‘INVITE’ the system offers the choice to invite users as writers or readers. By selecting a form of invitation, the chooseGroup() message activates the creation of sendRecObj. We describe the subsequent steps for the case of invitation as writers (See Fig. 15). First sendRecObj issues a query for all of the system users who have not joined the group yet and do not have pending writer invitations (they might have pending reader invitations, though). When all data are collected, displayUsers() lists the retrieved users creating an HTML form from which the owner/moderator can select all the users to be invited. The form is then submitted, with the ID of the group for which the invitation is performed and the set of selected users. The interaction with the database is finally performed by the PHP function mysql_query($sqlInsert), where the content of $sqlInsert is determined in the same way as described in Section 5.3.2.

5.3.5. Creating and updating groups

Any MADCOW user can create any number of groups, getting owner privileges (see Fig. 18).

MADCOW sets the creation date and the owner can set the other properties. The value for title is a unique name usually reflecting the group intent, which is detailed in the group description. Both properties are searchable as text, while category can be used for thematic searches. Upon group creation, MADCOW generates a unique identifier, and saves a record for the group in its database. Moderators can be selected at the time of group creation, while enrolling initial users. The owner can change any property at any moment.

5.3.6. Deleting groups

Group deletion may be performed manually by its owner, or be caused by operations such as union and subsumption. In any case, the effect on the annotations posted to the deleted groups depends on the adopted policy. There are three levels of policy:

1.

The general MADCOW policy.

2.

The local policy for a group established by its creator.

3.

The individual policies set by writers when submitting annotations.

The general policy is “when a group is deleted, all of its related annotations are converted to private ones”, to guarantee that no writer loses any produced annotation. The group owner can alter this by specifying that: (1) members from a deleted group migrate to some other designated group(s), with the same owner, together with the annotations posted to this group (see Fig. 19). This policy is determined by setting the afterDeleteType property to ‘TRANSFERRED’; (2) writers can choose how to manage the annotations they posted; (3) MADCOW is responsible for deleting them after their expiry dates. For case (1), when the owner tries to delete a designated group, a warning is issued.

The pending requests and/or invitations related to a deleted group are deleted as well. An option is provided whether to maintain or delete groups which get united, while subsumed groups are always deleted.

5.3.7. Logging activities

MADCOW maintains searchable logs of activities, storing records of actions relative to group creation, update, deletion, invitations, applications and operations applied on groups. Logs are maintained for all groups, even deleted ones. MADCOW users can search for general activities on a group, as well as for specific actions, e.g. group creation, invitation, or others. Such logs can also be searched for specific information about activities within a group.

6. User tests

We performed some user tests to measure the impact of introducing groups and group services to MADCOW. By measuring users’ activities before and after introducing groups, we noticed an increase in behaviours which could be interpreted as collaborative. We quantified the users’ tendency towards submitting group-related annotations by counting the number of such annotations and comparing them with the number of private and public ones (before and after introducing the groups).

A second set of tests was devoted to measuring the usability of the system. Users were asked to execute the operations and services provided for group management and to provide feedbacks. In this case, we performed both quantitative measurements and subjective attitude measurements [28] based on questionnaires. In particular, we used rating scales in the first test and selection from choices in the follow-up one.

Following the methodology in [17], the report for each test is structured as follows:

1.

Introduction: illustrates the design of the test, and the set of tools and/or methods used in its preparation.

2.

Participants: describes the nature of the participants.

3.

Execution: describes timing, location and collection methods.

4.

Analysis: presents and discusses results.

For all tests, we ran sessions in the computer labs of the faculty of Engineering and Information Technology in An-Najah National University, Palestine. The labs are supported with Dell high-performance i7 processor desktop computers connected with a high speed LAN, with a high speed fibre optic backbone university network. The participants were undergraduate students from different curricula.

For the first test, the experiment was also conducted in the University of L’Aquila, synchronously with An-Najah, at the Acquisition, Analysis, Visualization & Imaging Laboratory (AAVI LAB), equipped with 10 laptop Toshiba (i7, RAM 4 GB) connected with a high speed LAN. In this case, the participants were students from the Medicine and the Computer Science curricula [41].

6.1. Changes in collaboration

The first set of tests was devoted to studying if variations in collaboration among users emerged after giving the possibility of joining groups.

6.1.1. Introduction

The test was designed by considering public or group (i.e. non private) annotations as providing a basis for collaboration. Private annotations were considered averse to collaboration both when groups were present and when the only alternative was to create public annotations. Hence, we formulated hypotheses as H0: being in a group does not change the ratio of collaborative annotations, and H1: being in a group increases the ratio of collaborative annotations. We set the significance level at p=0.05. At first, participants familiarised with the annotation process without being aware of the existence of groups; in a second moment we offered the possibility of joining a group specifically devised for the topic on which they were supposed to collaborate. Both objective and subjective (answers to online questionnaire) data were collected. A set of computers was reserved for on-site tests, but participants were also encouraged to freely create annotations whenever and wherever they wanted, during the time span of the study, in order to simulate a natural annotation creation process.

6.1.2. Participants

20 undergraduate students, divided equally between the two universities and selected from different disciplines to avoid biases in the understanding of the suggested topic, were involved under our supervision. The rationale for conducting two different sessions in two different countries (communities) was to check if there were cultural influences on the propensity to collaboration. This also had some effect towards bias avoidance in the selection of participants.

6.1.3. Execution

The experiment was performed over 6 days. We illustrated the whole idea to participants and asked them to begin annotating. We indicated a specific topic, “Privacy concerns with social networking services”, with reference to which they could conduct online discussions, and we indicated a set of relevant Web sites. After two days we created a group concerning the topic, and invited participants to join it and keep on submitting annotations. For the created group, joining was left open. We also asked participants to fill an online questionnaire about the perceived utility of being in a group with respect to collaboration. Answers to the questions below were to be given on a 1–7 rating scale (1=low, 7=high).

1.

Did you find group members open to discuss ideas?

2.

Did you feel comfortable sharing your ideas with members?

3.

Did your knowledge increase by sharing ideas with members?

4.

Did being in a group make it easier for your ideas to be discussed?

6.1.4. Analysis

We observed the differences in behaviour between participants who had joined a group and participants who had not, and within participants before and after joining. Table 5 shows the variation in the number of submissions of annotations and reflects participants’ attention towards group submission. Public and private annotations dropped when posting annotations to a group became possible.

Table 5. Posted annotations before/after group.

PublicPrivateGrouped
76/3127/120/131

We performed a one-tailed t-Student test matching behaviours of participants before and after, comparing the ratios public/(public+private) and (public+group)/(public+group+private) for annotations posted before and after group formation. We found the change in ratio to be significant (p=0.018). Moreover, we calculated the average number of threads for public and group annotations (5.4, 7.8) considering threads as indicators of actual collaboration, and we measured the growth rate for membership (2/day).

Table 6 shows the answers to questions concerning improvement of openness, sharing of ideas, increase of knowledge and discussion of ideas, taken as indicators of the quality of collaboration. Fig. 20 shows the same results combined in the two groups of negative or neutral answers (1-4) and positive ones (5-7). A negative or neutral answer (the lower line) indicates that the participant did not notice any improvement. Overall, we observe a consistent positive perception (the upper line) of the effect of groups on collaboration.

From the collected data, we noticed:

1.

The number of public annotations decreased once groups were formed. We interpret this as a preference for group annotations over public ones when the intent is one of collaborating.

2.

3.

4.

Participants’ answers in questionnaire reflect a higher confidence for all the judgements on support to collaboration (openness, sharing ideas, knowledge and discussing ideas) increased after their group membership.

In general, the test results3 show an increased collaborative behaviour after the introduction of groups (consistent with the observation that increased understandability reflects better collaboration [13]).

6.2. Usability 1: group services

The second set of tests was devoted to assess usability of group-related services both on the owner’s and the participant’s side.

6.2.1. Introduction

The overall assessment regarded the manageability of the different tasks involved in the activities of setting up/managing groups and of participating in groups, as well as the overall usability of the interface.

6.2.2. Participants

For this test we involved eight undergraduate classes related to Information Technology and Computer Sciences in An-Najah National University. We conducted with them a public crash course to introduce the idea of Web annotation and illustrate the use of MADCOW. The most interested students enrolled in the test, for a total of 152 participants.

6.2.3. Execution

They were requested to register to MADCOW and install the toolbar to their Firefox browsers. Lab technicians also installed the same browser on the Lab computers to involve them in the process and ask them to manage the whole test. The test was performed over 15 days distributed into 5 separate sessions without previous training and without specifying topics of interaction. As in the test on collaboration, 3 computer labs where reserved, but testing was also ubiquitous in terms of both time and place. The experiment unfolded in phases: creating groups, inviting users to become members, requesting for group joins, performing annotation processes, and finally filling a questionnaire. Each class tutor created a set of groups for his/her course with different properties for each one. Tutors began to invite students to their groups and students sent join requests to tutors. During the test, both tutors and students tried all of the MADCOW group services: submitting annotations to groups, viewing annotations, isolating students in a group, and blacklisting some of them. At the end of the test period, tutors and students were asked to answer the following closed-ended (except question 7) questions online, concerning the understandability of the use of groups and their related properties.

1.

How understandable were the steps for creating/updating a group?

2.

How understandable were the steps for filling/updating the group properties?

3.

How understandable were the steps for deleting a group, including migrating its writers/readers to other groups?

4.

As a group owner, which method of group joining do you prefer?

5.

As a prospective member, which method of joining do you prefer?

6.

How do you categorize the steps for joining a group (easy, vague, hard)?

7.

Do you suggest other group properties? If yes, write them down.

8.

Are the steps of invitation or apply request to join a group adequate?

9.

With respect to annotations submitted to groups, are the contents of submission window clear?

10.

Are the steps of creating annotations and saving them in your groups clear?

11.

Is the user role “reader” clear with respect to groups?

12.

Is the submission to non-group clear?

13.

Are the data related to annotations appearing in your account adequate?

14.

What is the least understandable operation in the system?

Participants were also asked for specific comments and suggestions, if they had problems with understanding the interface.

6.2.4. Analysis

At the end of the test period, 72 groups had been created, 31 of them had been deleted, members of 17 deleted groups were transferred to other groups, 51 groups were updated (including modification of group properties and management of moderators and blacklists), 719 invitations were sent (687 accepted, 26 refused, 6 not answered), 125 requests were released (106 accepted, 10 refused, 9 not answered), all groups totaled 529 members (35 members came from the transfer process for the 17 deleted groups), 337 annotations where submitted to the system and 2164 group management operations were executed, not considering not answered invitations and requests.

Fig. 21 compares the percentages of different operations performed where percentage scaling for number of operations per operation category is used.

Fig. 22 shows a graphical representation for preferences for the group join operation in Table 9, where “Any One” means any method is acceptable for both users and group owners. It is clear that most participants prefer the public join, the reason possibly being that it does not need extra steps.

Table 12 shows results for question 14 on the least understandable operation. It is clear that most participants grasped the idea behind introducing groups and their related operations. Problems with non-understandable operations are concentrated in a specific set. This is also related to the concentration in the same menu of the operations for updating group properties, assigning/deassigning moderators and building blacklisted list of members4.

Table 7 shows that the average time for updating properties of a group is less than half that for creating a group. Indeed, while creation requires considering all group properties (even if simply to accept the defaults), updating needs only to take into account the properties one is interested in. One may also remark that the major difference in average duration is between the addition of new members by invitation or by accepting join requests. Again, invitation involves a selection from the whole set of MADCOW users, and is usually done in bulks, while in the second case, the owner or moderator only needs to scan through small sets of applications.

Table 8, Table 9, Table 10, Table 11, Table 12 indicate good feedback from participants who deemed acceptable the understandability for all tested operations, the ease of use of the system, and the steps for executing different operations.

Concerning the free entering of comments, the suggestions provided were not specifically related to group properties and operations, but mostly concerned the addition of features such as the inclusion of a chat system among users. Others left the field of questionnaire empty. Data in the table also reflect good understandability for the steps needed to send join invitations or applications, the different data fields and items appear in the annotation submission popup window, how to create and save annotations with their different related data, the role of reader privilege and the idea behind it, selecting the appropriate annotation type (public, private, grouped), and displaying annotations from system portal and understanding their related properties.

6.3. Usability 2: Operations

The appropriateness of the proposed operations on groups and of the interfaces provided for them was assessed in a follow-up on the experiment described in Section 6.2.

6.3.1. Introduction

The tests described in Section 6.2 were complemented with a questionnaire concerned with the application of the operations on groups by their owners. We used specific questions to assess the appropriateness of the group management operations and the usability of the interfaces provided for them. The questions were the following:

1.

How much did you understand group operations? (Understanding)

2.

How easy did you find executing a group operation? (Ease)

3.

How adequate did you feel the number of steps for each operation? (Feeling)

4.

Are available actions evident? (Obviousness)

5.

Is the sequence of actions to perform an operation good? (Sequence)

6.

Which operation did you find difficult? (Difficult Operation)

7.

How many correct activities did you perform for each operation? (Correct Activities)

6.3.2. Participants

The participants were a subset of those involved in the tests described in 6.2; in particular, we selected those who had been group owners in the test described in Section 6.2, since they had become familiar with group services.

6.3.3. Execution

The Questionnaire was administered, at the end of the first phase of activities, to the tutors and students who created groups and applied operations.

Table 13, Table 14, Table 15 reflect an overall positive feedback from participants with respect to understandability and ease of use of the steps for executing groups’ operations. As Table 16 shows, the time required by the Subsumption operation is much less than for the other operations. Indeed, the interaction needed to complete the operation is very simple: the user selects two groups, and the system checks whether the operation meets the preconditions for the operation. The other operations, on the contrary, require that the user select a set of members to which the operation has to be applied, where the size of the selection affects the overall execution time.

6.4. Final comments

6.4.1. Threats to validity

The participants to the tests were recruited in courses held by colleagues, hence no real experimentation in the wild occurred. However, they were not directly students of any of the authors, so they could feel free in expressing their opinions. The time frame for observation was quite restricted in the first experiment and there was an explicit suggestion to cooperate. However, the observed phenomena, in particular the decrease of public annotation, that we had not foreseen, indicate that they adopted personal strategies.

6.4.2. Participants’ cultural affiliation

Results collected from the two sessions conducted in the first experimental test showed an improvement in the collaboration among participants after the introduction of groups, regardless of the nation and culture of participants.

6.4.3. Corrective actions

After the tests, we addressed the problems with the least understandable operations and changed the processes to assign moderators and blacklist writers. In particular, we added other two list boxes to the update menu to include the assigned moderators and the blacklisted writers. In the new interface, when a group owner selects moderators or writers to be blacklisted, the selected user names are migrated to the new list boxes (and deleted from the selection list). The opposite migration takes place in the process of deassigning moderators or removing writers from the blacklist box5.

7. Conclusions and future work

We have extended the MADCOW Web annotation system with group capabilities. Users can create and delete groups, or modify their properties, and manage social actions such as inviting other users to join their groups or applying for participation in other groups, all activities being maintained in inspectable logs. Data privacy and security issues are taken into account, especially with respect to group deletion in the management of group-merging processes. New group-based services are then available for MADCOW users wanting to form new groups or to join existing ones.

Supervised experimental tests have been conducted, indicating that groups seem to increase the possibility of collaborating through annotations, and recording an overall satisfaction with the proposed tools.

The tests also highlighted two types of problems related to manual management of joining activities: its cost in time and irrelevance of membership, i.e. owners end up inviting people not interested or users end up applying for groups not related to their interests. We are attacking these issues by endowing MADCOW with some form of automatic suggestion. In particular, we have started including matching techniques based on the association of groups with domain ontologies: terms in an ontology can be matched with terms considered significant for a user, based on direct input of query terms, or on the tags adorning annotations by that user. Another source of suggestions is the coincidence between pages annotated by members of a group and those annotated by prospective members. The first tests have shown significant improvements in the quality of suggestions and in the time required to identify relevant groups [5], [6].

The functions fst, snd, and thd return, the first, second, and third component of a tuple, respectively and op is any unitary operation defined for group. The conditional operator bool?exp1: exp2 returns the value of exp1 if bool evaluates to true, the value of exp2 otherwise.
